comments.en: Vocabulary defined by the European Union Agency for Railways to describe the concepts and relationships related to the European railway infrastructure and the vehicles authorized to operate over it.

comment.en: A vehicle type that has been authorized to operate on the EU railway infrastructure.
Abstract class representing vehicle categories
A running track that is used for train service movements.
Abstract class representing the different existing types of Operational Points
Abstract class representing vehicle manufacturer companies
A specific track abstraction usee to represent a micro link switch that is possible inside a micro node.
Abstract class representing gauging profiles

prefLabel.value: Passenger Coach (incl. sleeping cars, restaurant, etc.)

comment.en: Abstract class representing vehicle sub categories
An abstraction of an operational point, used to provide a simple topological description of the railway infrastructure.

An operational point (OP) means any location for train service operations, where train services may begin and end or change route, and where passenger or freight services may be provided; operational point means also any location at boundaries between Member States or infrastructure managers.
A port to enter or exit a micro node. Represents the connection between a micro link and a micro node.
An abstraction of a track that represent a physical rail connection between two different micro nodes.
A railway tunnel is an excavation or a construction around the track provided to allow the railway to pass for example higher land, buildings or water.

definition.value: Rolling stock which is designed and built to operate on underground sections and tunnels of not more than 5 km in length, with side evacuation available is defined as category A
Rolling stock which is designed and built to operate in all tunnels of the trans-European Network is defined as category B
None of rolling stock fire categories A or B shall be applied on a tunnel

comment.en: Abstract class representing fire categories of rolling stock. Rolling stock admitted in tunnels shall belong to either of the fire safety categories A and B
